What you need to know:

For someone who was starting from scratch, she did not have enough capital and lenders were not willing to advance her credit.The EU, which is Kenya’s main market for horticulture produce, had initially capped the sampling at five per cent, with the doubling of the sample size expected to hit farmers and make the produce more expensive in the world market.King’ori works on a piece of land she leased for five years. She pays Sh8, 000 per year per acre to lease the land.She has also been able to fence the land and come up with a drip irrigation system for the whole land using the amount she received from YEDF.